observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Deduct the 10 percent retention money on the first progress payment equivalent to 40 percent of the value of works on the Construction of Covered Sidewalk and Parking Space at Barangay Poblacion from the succeeding progress billing; 

Deduct the 10 percent retention money on the first progress payment equivalent to 30.582 percent of the value of works on the Construction of Multi-Purpose Building at Barangay Batancaoa from the succeeding progress billing; 

Subject first progress payments of more than 50 percent of the works and one-time payments for 100 percent completion, with retention money equivalent to at least 10 percent of the 50 percent of the value of works for projects that are satisfactorily undertaken and on schedule; otherwise, impose additional retention money on the remaining progress payments equivalent to 10 percent; and

Allow substitution of the retention money only when the project is satisfactorily undertaken and on schedule supported with letter-request of the contractor.

We recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Engineer to:

Strictly monitor and inspect all completed projects during the one-year defects liability period to determine any defects for correction/repair by the concerned contractors;

Observe the issuance of CFA one year after project completion date;

Require the concerned contractors to post the required warranty security before the issuance of CFA; and

Furnish the Audit Team copies of issued CFA and proofs that the contractor posted the required warranty security.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to request for snap shots from the bank every end of the month or register all the bank accounts in an online banking facility/system available in the depository banks of the LGU to obtain timely bank statements and furnish copy to the Municipal Accountant for the preparation and submission of the monthly BRS within the prescribed period;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the bank officials with respect to identified bank errors for correction/adjustment to reflect the correct balance of bank account of each fund maintained with the bank; otherwise, if the bank would not allow any adjustments in its records due to late notice as per bank policy, require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to cause the fund transfer of the erroneous deposits to the respective bank accounts;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to counter check the machine validated deposit slips upon deposit of collections for timely identification and communication of any errors, and the Municipal Accountant, through the Municipal Treasurer, to inform the bank upon discovery of any bank errors or other bank reconciling items identified in the BRS; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to draw journal entry voucher to reflect the correct balance of Cash in Bank – SAGANA Fund and Cash in Bank – SEF in the books of accounts.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to record:

Advance payments for RPT and SET as income when they are actually earned;


Discounts granted for prompt payment of property taxes due for the year as Discount on RPT – Basic or Discount on SET;

Discounts given to taxpayer for paying property tax in advance as Discount on Advance Payments; and

Collections on penalties from delinquent property taxes as Tax Revenue - Fines and Penalties – Property Taxes.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the PSDS or co-chairman of the LSB to prepare the SEF Budget using the prescribed form and ensure proper classification of proposed expenditures as to allotment class to avoid the recurrence of the noted deficiency;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Record the proposed adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in the financial statements as at year-end and ensure that all transactions of the LGU are properly recorded in the books of accounts; 

Ensure that all supporting documents attached to the disbursement vouchers are properly accomplished to provide complete information on the transactions of the LGU;  

Require warranty security on the succeeding procurement of goods either through imposition of retention money or acceptance of a special bank guarantee; and

Impose LD to the concerned supplier amounting to ₱3,986.01 for the late delivery of printers.

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Secure Sales Invoice or Charge Invoice to support the issuance of the Collection Receipt from the supplier to substantiate the transaction incurred; and

Accept Sales Invoice or ORs as evidence of receipt of payment. Collection receipt may be accepted only when a charge invoice was initially issued by the supplier.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to account the succeeding collections on Building Permit Fees in the Report of Collections and Deposits as 80 percent accruing to the General Fund, 15 percent for OBO operations as trust funds and 5 percent share of the DPWH Secretary which shall be remitted to the Bureau of Treasury;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant to monitor the remittance of the five percent share of the DPWH to the BTr; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to take-up the proposed adjusting journal entries in the books of accounts for the correct presentation of account balances in the financial statement; and 

Require the Municipal Engineering Office as the OBO to prepare a Program of Work detailing the manner of utilization of the 15 percent share from the collection of building permit fees, and submit the same to the DPWH Secretary through the NBCDO.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the PSDS or co-chairman of the LSB to:

prepare the SEF Budget using the required SEF Budget Preparation Form which shall be presented by program, project and activity and by allotment class;

specifically identify the PPAs in the SEF budget to avoid provision of appropriations couched in generic terms; and

strictly adhere with the prescribed timelines in the preparation and approval of the SEF budget;

Direct the BAC to ensure that only relevant specifications and performance requirements of the goods/materials to be purchased are indicated in the PR without reference to brand names;

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents to the Audit Team for evaluation; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all claims are supported with complete and proper documentation before endorsing them for payment.

We recommended that Management insure all the insurable properties relevant in the delivery of public service to provide safeguard against substantial losses in the event of damage to, or loss of, properties brought by fortuitous events by requiring the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to identify the insurable assets 



and to submit the inventory report to the GSIS consistent with the provision of COA Circular No. 2018-002 dated May 31, 2018 for evaluation; 



and to instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to appropriate funds needed for the payment of premiums.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and GSO - Designate with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects to each road network based on the Program of Works;
Require the GSO - Designate to prepare the Road Map and instruct the GSO Designate, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile the inventory of local roads with the recorded road networks in the books of accounts;
Require GSO - Designate to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period;
Create an inventory committee assigned to primarily handle the inventory of local road network system;
Instruct the Head of the Inventory Committee to conduct annual inventory of road networks using the RPCLRN; and
Upon reconciliation of records, require the Municipal Accountant to adjust the balance of road networks in the books of accounts and maintain subsidiary ledger for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to effect fund transfer of all the unexpended/unobligated balances of 2020 QRF and MF-MOOE and the Municipal Treasurer to issue check to the Trust Fund books for easy monitoring of the utilization and to ensure availability of the fund to support disaster risk and reduction and management activities of LDRRMC.



We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant stop the practice of using receivable and payable accounts in the recording of the transfer of unexpended calamity fund from General Fund to Trust Fund books;



and to effect the physical transfer of cash prior to closing of the books.

We recommended that Management require the BAC to:

Update the form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all transactions involving procurement undertaken through alternative methods to indicate the ABC, and other terms and conditions of the contract;



Ensure that the RFQs, as a formal letter from the LGU, are signed by the BAC Chairman;



Require the suppliers to indicate the brand of goods they are offering and other necessary information that may affect the final evaluation of the offers; and



Prepare Abstract of Quotations after receiving and evaluating the price quotations received by them and BAC Resolutions Recommending to the HoPE the Award of Contract in favor of the supplier with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation.

We recommended that Management require the BAC to:
Update the form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all transactions involving procurement undertaken through alternative methods to indicate the ABC, and other terms and conditions of the contract;
Ensure that the RFQs, as a formal letter from the LGU, are signed by the BAC Chairman;
Require the suppliers to indicate the brand of goods they are offering and other necessary information that may affect the final evaluation of the offers; and
Prepare Abstract of Quotations after receiving and evaluating the price quotations received by them and BAC Resolutions Recommending to the HoPE the Award of Contract in favor of the supplier with the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Quotation.

We recommended that Management:
a. Require the contractors to immediately fast track the completion of the projects to avoid rescindment of contracts as stipulated therein pursuant to Section 68 of RA 9184;
b. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to conduct inventory of work accomplishment by the contractor;
c. Impose liquidated damages to contractor concerned relative to the incurrence of delay in the construction of projects at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.10%) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay;
d. Intensify monitoring of projects in order to avoid recurrence of delay of other projects; and
e. Submit Suspension and Resume Orders, if any, on the said projects for validation and evaluation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
1. Inform the General Services Office or Property Officer to periodically render Report on Local Road Networks, and furnish copies to the concerned offices. Also, Municipal Engineer’s Office should provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer or Property Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
2. Create an Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of public infrastructure specially the local road networks;
3. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each individual road networks; and
4. Ensure coordination among LGU Offices to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System.

